        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity

We take the spectrum information for 12CO 2-1 from Winters et al (2010). 
We are only interested in the central ~ 4" of the source.
Analysing the CO 2-1 spectrum, we obtain a line peak value of 0.7 Jy/beam, with a beam of 1.67 X 0.94 arcsec. Assuming that the flux is distributed uniformly inside the beam, we obtain a flux of 0.11 Jy/beam, with a beam of 0.25 arcsec. Therefore, with the requested rms noise of 5 mJy/beam at 0.16 km/s resolution, we will detect the 12Co 2-1 line at 22 sigma.

Since we are also interested in detecting the plateau in the spectrum. From Winters et al data, we can see that the flux for that part of the spectrum is ~ 0.2 Jy/beam. Consequently, we will detect this feature at ~ 6 sigma, which is good enough to do our analysis.

The sensitivity calculation is based on the 12CO 2-1 line intensity. For the other molecules, we estimated the fluxes as there is no reported observations so far. 
The CO molecular species are own main target for this study, and the rest of the molecules are complementary, not affecting the project the level of detection it will get.

According to OT, an rms of 5 mJy/beam in a channel of 0.16 km/s, using a pwv of 1.26 mm (4th Octile), will require an integration time on source of ~ 41.5 min. Including calibration, the total time for this proposal is estimated in ~ 1.4 hr.

For continuum, we will have a minimum bandwidth of ~ 2GHz. This provides a sensitivity of ~ 40 microJy. Since the continuum level we expect from our source is ~ 16 mJy, we will be able to detect it at ~ 400 sigma.


Imaging

Althoug our source is extended, we are only interested in the inner region. This region fits perfectly in the primary beam of the 12-m array. Our source does not have a complicated structure, making the imaging reliable in the observing mode we propose.


Correlator setup

We chose the correlator setup to be able to observe all our lines at a resolution of ~ 0.16 km/s. Whenever necessary, we chose to average several channels.


Calibration

The standard calibration that ALMA provides is adequate for our project.


Bandpass accuracy

Our source does not possess any characteristic that require a high bandpass accuracy, therefore the accuracy achieved at band 6 is more than adequate for this project.


Data rate

The data rate for this project is 12.4 MB/sec. Such data rate is needed to be able to observe at 0.16 km/s spectral resolution. Such fine resolution is needed to resolve and fit properly the spectral lines which present a narrow component.




</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
